t to the Foreigners’ Office, and many others—as well as the stories they tell one another, Feldman-Savelsberg enlivens our thinking about migrants’ lives and the networks and repertoires that they draw on to find stability and, ultimately, belonging. Placing women’s individual voices within international social contexts, this book unveils new, intimate links between the geographical and the generational as they intersect in the dreams, frustrations, uncertainties, and resolve of strong women holding families together across continents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBelonging (Social psychology) - Cameroon. 0aBelonging (Social psychology)zCameroon. 0aBelonging (Social psychology). 0aCameroonianszGermanyzBerlinxEthnic identity. 0aCameroonianszGermanyzBerlin. 0aImmigrant familieszGermanyzBerlinxPsychological aspects. 0aMotherhoodxPsychological aspects. 70(DE-588)4012089-20(DE-627)1063500130(DE-576)208896791aDiasporagReligion2gnd 70(DE-588)4018202-20(DE-627)1042707050(DE-576)208923209aFrau2gnd 70(DE-588)4040949-10(DE-627)1062210940(DE-576)209042818aMutter2gnd 70(DE-588)4130642-90(DE-627)1057010410(DE-576)209620706aLebensbedingungen2gnd 70(DE-588)4162051-30(DE-627)1048191540(DE-576)209870583aInternationale Migration2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aBerlin.  aCameroon.  aGermany.  abelonging.  achildren.  alegal consciousness.  amigration.  amotherhood.  areproduction.  asocial networks.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022638974540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226389912423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226389912/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016